# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: obj-3d-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] In 3D computer graphics, **3D modeling** is the process of developing a mathematical coordinate-based representation of a surface of an object (inanimate or living) in three dimensions via specialized software by manipulating edges, vertices, and polygons in a simulated 3D space.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Three-dimensional (3D) models represent a physical body using a collection of points in 3D space, connected by various geometric entities such as triangles, lines, curved surfaces, etc.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Being a collection of data (points and other information), 3D models can be created manually, algorithmically (procedural modeling), or by scanning.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Their surfaces may be further defined with texture mapping.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The product is called a 3D model, while someone who works with 3D models may be referred to as a 3D artist or a 3D modeler.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] A 3D model can also be displayed as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering or used in a computer simulation of physical phenomena.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] 3D models may be created automatically or manually.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The 3D model can be physically created using 3D printing devices that form 2D layers of the model with three-dimensional material, one layer at a time.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Without a 3D model, a 3D print is not possible.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] 3D modeling software is a class of 3D computer graphics software used to produce 3D models.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] 3D models are now widely used anywhere in 3D graphics and CAD but their history predates the widespread use of 3D graphics on personal computers.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] In the past, many computer games used pre-rendered images of 3D models as sprites before computers could render them in real-time.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The designer can then see the model in various directions and views, this can help the designer see if the object is created as intended to compared to their original vision.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Seeing the design this way can help the designer or company figure out changes or improvements needed to the product.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Simple wireframes were the first versions of early 3D models, which were mainly used to view construction plans and mechanical parts.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Better graphics hardware and software allowed for the creation of solid and surface models in the 1970s and 1980s, giving designers a more realistic and clear representation of physical objects.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] By the 1990s, parametric modeling became popular, letting designers change a model by changing its basic parameters instead of redrawing it from scratch.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Thanks to virtual reality, artificial intelligence and generative design tools, 3D modeling today goes past engineering and is influencing fields like animation, gaming, product design and cinema.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Solid and shell modeling can create functionally identical objects.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Differences between them are mostly variations in the way they are created and edited and conventions of use in various fields and differences in types of approximations between the model and reality.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Shell models must be manifold (having no holes or cracks in the shell) to be meaningful as a real object.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] For example, in a shell model of a cube, all six sides must be connected with no gaps in the edges or the corners.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Polygonal meshes (and to a lesser extent, subdivision surfaces) are by far the most common representation.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Level sets are a useful representation for deforming surfaces that undergo many topological changes, such as fluids.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The process of transforming representations of objects, such as the middle point coordinate of a sphere and a point on its circumference, into a polygon representation of a sphere is called tessellation.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] This step is used in polygon-based rendering, where objects are broken down from abstract representations ("primitives") such as spheres, cones etc., to so-called *meshes*, which are nets of interconnected triangles.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Meshes of triangles (instead of e.g., squares) are popular as they have proven to be easy to rasterize (the surface described by each triangle is planar, so the projection is always convex).
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Polygon representations are not used in all rendering techniques, and in these cases the tessellation step is not included in the transition from abstract representation to rendered scene.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The modeling stage consists of shaping individual objects that are later used in the scene.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] In some cases, there is no strict distinction between these phases; in such cases, modeling is just part of the scene creation process (this is the case, for example, with Caligari trueSpace and Realsoft 3D).
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] 3D models can also be created using the technique of Photogrammetry with dedicated programs such as RealityCapture, Metashape and 3DF Zephyr.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Cleanup and further processing can be performed with applications such as MeshLab, the GigaMesh Software Framework, netfabb or MeshMixer.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Photogrammetry creates models using algorithms to interpret the shape and texture of real-world objects and environments based on photographs taken from many angles of the subject.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Complex materials such as blowing sand, clouds, and liquid sprays are modeled with particle systems, and are a mass of 3D coordinates which have either points, polygons, texture splats or sprites assigned to them.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] There are a variety of 3D modeling programs that can be used in the industries of engineering, interior design, film and others.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Each 3D modeling software has specific capabilities and can be utilized to fulfill demands for the industry.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Many programs include export options to form a g-code, applicable to additive or subtractive manufacturing machinery.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] G-code (computer numerical control) works with automated technology to form a real-world rendition of 3D models.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] This code is a specific set of instructions to carry out steps of a product's manufacturing.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The first widely available commercial application of human virtual models appeared in 1998 on the Lands' End web site.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The human virtual models were created by the company My Virtual Mode Inc. and enabled users to create a model of themselves and try on 3D clothing.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] There are several modern programs that allow for the creation of virtual human models (Poser being one example).
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The development of cloth simulation software such as Marvelous Designer, CLO3D and Optitex, has enabled artists and fashion designers to model dynamic 3D clothing on the computer.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Dynamic 3D clothing is used for virtual fashion catalogs, as well as for dressing 3D characters for video games, 3D animation movies, for digital doubles in movies, as a creation tool for digital fashion brands, as well as for making clothes for avatars in virtual worlds such as SecondLife.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Disadvantages compared to 2D photorealistic rendering may include a software learning curve and difficulty achieving certain photorealistic effects.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Some photorealistic effects may be achieved with special rendering filters included in the 3D modeling software.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] For the best of both worlds, some artists use a combination of 3D modeling followed by editing the 2D computer-rendered images from the 3D model.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] A large market for 3D models (as well as 3D-related content, such as textures, scripts, etc.) exists—either for individual models or large collections.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Several online marketplaces for 3D content allow individual artists to sell content that they have created, including TurboSquid, MyMiniFactory,Patreon,Sketchfab, CGTrader, and Cults.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Often, the artists' goal is to get additional value out of assets they have previously created for projects.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] By doing so, artists can earn more money out of their old content, and companies can save money by buying pre-made models instead of paying an employee to create one from scratch.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] These marketplaces typically split the sale between themselves and the artist that created the asset, artists get 40% to 95% of the sales according to the marketplace.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] In most cases, the artist retains ownership of the 3D model while the customer only buys the right to use and present the model.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Some artists sell their products directly in their own stores, offering their products at a lower price by not using intermediaries.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The architecture, engineering and construction (AEC) industry is the biggest market for 3D modeling, with an estimated value of $12.13 billion by 2028.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] This is due to the increasing adoption of 3D modeling in the AEC industry, which helps to improve design accuracy, reduce errors and omissions and facilitate collaboration among project stakeholders.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Over the last several years numerous marketplaces specializing in 3D rendering and printing models have emerged.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Some of the 3D printing marketplaces are a combination of models sharing sites, with or without a built in e-com capability.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Some of those platforms also offer 3D printing services on demand, software for model rendering and dynamic viewing of items.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The term 3D printing or three-dimensional printing is a form of additive manufacturing technology where a three-dimensional object is created from successive layers of material.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Objects can be created without the need for complex and expensive molds or assembly of multiple parts.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] 3D printing allows ideas to be prototyped and tested without having to go through a more time-consuming production process.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] 3D models can be purchased from online markets and printed by individuals or companies using commercially available 3D printers, enabling the home-production of objects such as spare parts and even medical equipment.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Open-source tools (for instance Blender, FreeCAD, MeshLab, OpenSCAD) coexist with commercial packages (some examples are: Autodesk Maya/3ds Max/Fusion 360, SolidWorks, CATIA, Cinema 4D, ZBrush, Rhino, Houdini, SketchUp, CLO 3D/Marvelous Designer, Revit, Archicad).
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] The RDF representation of 3D models can be used in reasoning, which enables intelligent 3D applications which, for example, can automatically compare two 3D models by volume.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Overall, these examples are an illustration of 3D modelling being a tool of general purpose representational layer that creates a bridge between sensing to analysis, design, communication and fabrication.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Despite 3D modelling being widely adopted in various domains, several constraints shape how the technology is utilized.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Access and cost remain an issue in many regions of the world.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Commercial licences, training, and capable hardware can be difficult to find in select regions.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] It can also be out of reach for students and small studios that cannot afford it.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Open-source ecosystems and school programs can aid in making this less of an issue, but availability and support are uneven which in turn creates an equity gap in who can learn and apply 3D modelling.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Workflow complexity is another limitation.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] To practice 3D modelling effectively it requires knowledge of many different things.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] A 3D modelling specialist needs to understand topology, UV mapping, rigging, simulation and rendering for DCC.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] For CAD/CAM modelling parametric constraints, tolerances and manufacturing constraints must be known by the developer.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Information schema and coordination are both required for BIM.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Moving assets between tools can introduce incompatibility issues (meshes vs.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] NURBS/solids/parametric features; unit scaling; normals; material definitions), and format conversions may cause data loss without careful management.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] At scale, energy consumption can be large (this is due to high resolution simulations and rendering and dense 3D scans), which directs teams to try and optimize design complexity and adopting more efficient pipelines.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] In research and heritage work, there is another constraint where ethical and policy questions include provenance, licensing and representation (how “authoritative” a reconstruction should be labelled), especially as these reconstruction are utilized for public communication and educational purposes.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Finally, classroom and outreach deployments must take into account pedagogical support: learners need step by step guidance and clear examples and models to follow.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Without this, the tool’s complexity will be more of a barrier that slows students down instead of enabling them to understand and be creative.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] In 3D modeling, simulations are digital processes that copy how things behave in the real world, in a virtual space.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] Without creating actual prototypes, it lets designers and animators test how objects move, interact, or react to forces.
[src:obj-3d-format/3d-modeling] By recreating processes such as collisions, fluid movement, fabric draping, or particle motion, simulations help increase design accuracy, enhance visual effects, and save both time and materials.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The OBJ file format is a simple data-format that represents 3D geometry alone – namely, the position of each vertex, the UV position of each texture coordinate vertex, vertex normals, and the faces that make each polygon defined as a list of vertices, and texture vertices.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Vertices are stored in a counter-clockwise order by default, making explicit declaration of face normals unnecessary.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] OBJ coordinates have no units, but OBJ files can contain scale information in a human readable comment line.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Anything following a hash character (#) is a comment.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] An OBJ file may contain vertex data, free-form curve/surface attributes, elements, free-form curve/surface body statements, connectivity between free-form surfaces, grouping and display/render attribute information.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A vertex is specified via a line starting with the letter `v`.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] That is followed by (x,y,z[,w]) coordinates.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The point (x,y,z,w) corresponds to the point (x/w,y/w,z/w).
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A right-hand coordinate system is used to specify the coordinate locations.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Some applications support vertex colors, by putting red, green and blue values after x y and z (this precludes specifying w).
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A free-form geometry statement can be specified in a line starting with the string `vp`.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Define points in parameter space of a curve or surface.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] `u` only is required for curve points, `u` and `v` for surface points and control points of non-rational trimming curves, and `u`, `v` and `w` (weight) for control points of rational trimming curves.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Faces are defined using lists of vertex, texture and normal indices in the format vertex_index/texture_index/normal_index for which each index starts at 1 and increases corresponding to the order in which the referenced element was defined.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Polygons such as quadrilaterals can be defined by using more than three indices.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] OBJ files also support free-form geometry which use curves and surfaces to define objects, such as NURBS surfaces.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A valid vertex index matches the corresponding vertex elements of a previously defined vertex list.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] If an index is positive then it refers to the offset in that vertex list, starting at 1.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] If an index is negative then it relatively refers to the end of the vertex list, -1 referring to the last element.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Each face can contain three or more vertices.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Optionally, texture coordinate indices can be used to specify texture coordinates when defining a face.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] To add a texture coordinate index to a vertex index when defining a face, one must put a slash immediately after the vertex index and then put the texture coordinate index.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] No spaces are permitted before or after the slash.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A valid texture coordinate index starts from 1 and matches the corresponding element in the previously defined list of texture coordinates.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Each face can contain three or more elements.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Optionally, normal indices can be used to specify normal vectors for vertices when defining a face.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] To add a normal index to a vertex index when defining a face, one must put a second slash after the texture coordinate index and then put the normal index.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A valid normal index starts from 1 and matches the corresponding element in the previously defined list of normals.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] As texture coordinates are optional, one can define geometry without them, but one must put two slashes after the vertex index before putting the normal index.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Records starting with the letter "l" (lowercase L) specify the order of the vertices which build a polyline.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] OBJ files support higher-order surfaces using several different kinds of interpolation, such as Taylor and B-splines, although support for those features in third party file readers is far from universal.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] OBJ files also do not support mesh hierarchies or any kind of animation or deformation, such as vertex skinning or mesh morphing.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Materials that describe the visual aspects of the polygons are stored in external .mtl files.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] More than one external MTL material file may be referenced from within the OBJ file.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The .mtl file may contain one or more named material definitions.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] This tag specifies the material name for the element following it.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The material name matches a named material definition in an external .mtl file.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Named objects and polygon groups are specified via the following tags.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Smooth shading across polygons is enabled by smoothing groups.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] OBJ files, due to their list structure, are able to reference vertices, normals, etc. either by their absolute position (1 represents the first defined vertex, N representing the Nth defined vertex), or by their relative position (-1 represents the latest defined vertex).
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] However, not all software supports the latter approach, and conversely some software inherently writes only the latter form (due to the convenience of appending elements without needing to recalculate vertex offsets, etc.), leading to occasional incompatibilities.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The **Material Template Library** format (MTL) or .MTL File Format is a companion file format to .OBJ, also defined by Wavefront Technologies, that describes surface shading (material) properties of objects within one or more .OBJ files.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The standard has widespread support among different computer software packages, making it a useful format for interchange of materials.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The MTL format, although still widely used, is outdated and does not fully support later technologies such as specular maps and parallax maps.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] However, due to the open and intuitive nature of the format, these can easily be added with a custom MTL file generator.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The MTL format defines a number of formats.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A single `.mtl` file may define multiple materials.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The ambient color of the material is declared using `Ka`.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Color definitions are in RGB where each channel's value is between 0 and 1.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Similarly, the diffuse color is declared using `Kd`.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The specular color is declared using `Ks`, and weighted using the specular exponent `Ns`.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] This is referred to as being *dissolved*.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Unlike real transparency, the result does not depend upon the thickness of the object.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A value of 1.0 for "d" (*dissolve*) is the default and means fully opaque, as does a value of 0.0 for "Tr".
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Dissolve works on all illumination models.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Transparent materials can additionally have a Transmission Filter Color, specified with "Tf".
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A material can also have an optical density for its surface.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] This is also known as index of refraction.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] A value of 1.0 means that light does not bend as it passes through an object.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Increasing the optical density increases the amount of bending.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Glass has an index of refraction of about 1.5.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Values of less than 1.0 produce bizarre results and are not recommended.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Multiple illumination models are available, per material.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Note that it is not required to set a transparent illumination model in order to achieve transparency with "d" or "Tr", and in modern usage illum models are often not specified, even with transparent materials.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Textured materials use the same properties as above, and additionally define texture maps.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Below is an example of a common material file.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] See the full Wavefront file format reference for more details.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Texture map statements may also have option parameters (see full spec).
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Because of the ease in parsing the files, and the unofficial spreading of the file format, files may contain vendor specific alterations.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] According to the spec, options are supposed to precede the texture filename.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] However, at least one vendor generates files with options at the end.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] The creators of the online 3D editing and modeling tool, Clara.io, proposed extending the MTL format to enable specifying physically-based rendering (PBR) maps and parameters.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] This extension has been subsequently adopted by Blender and TinyObjLoader.
[src:obj-3d-format/material-template-library] Further proposed extensions come from the DirectXMesh toolkit for Microsoft's DirectX engine, allowing the ability to define a model's pre-compiled RMA material.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] In 3D computer graphics and solid modeling, a **polygon mesh** is a collection of **vertices**, **edges** and **faces** that define the shape of a polyhedral object's surface.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] It simplifies rendering, as in a wire-frame model.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The faces usually consist of triangles (triangle mesh), quadrilaterals (quads), or other simple convex polygons (n-gons).
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] A polygonal mesh may also be more generally composed of concave polygons, or even polygons with holes.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The study of polygon meshes is a large sub-field of computer graphics (specifically 3D computer graphics) and geometric modeling.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Different representations of polygon meshes are used for different applications and goals.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The variety of operations performed on meshes includes Boolean logic (Constructive solid geometry), smoothing, and simplification.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Algorithms also exist for ray tracing, collision detection, and rigid-body dynamics with polygon meshes.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] If the mesh's edges are rendered instead of the faces, then the model becomes a wireframe model.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Several methods exist for mesh generation, including the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Volumetric meshes are distinct from polygon meshes in that they explicitly represent both the surface and interior region of a structure, while polygon meshes only explicitly represent the surface (the volume is implicit).
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Objects created with polygon meshes must store different types of elements.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] These include vertices, edges, faces, polygons and surfaces.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] In many applications, only vertices, edges and either faces or polygons are stored.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] A renderer may support only 3-sided faces, so polygons must be constructed of many of these, as shown above.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] However, many renderers either support quads and higher-sided polygons, or are able to convert polygons to triangles on the fly, making it unnecessary to store a mesh in a triangulated form.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] A vertex in computer graphics terms is a data structure that describes the position of a point in 2, 3 or 4D space on a surface along with optional attributes - other values used to render the object correctly.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Most attributes of a vertex represent vectors in the space to be rendered.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] These vectors are typically 2 (*x, y*) or 3 (*x, y, z*) dimensional and can include a fourth homogeneous coordinate (*w*)..
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] In real-time rendering these properties are used by a vertex shader or vertex pipeline.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Attributes can include position, color, reflectance, specularity, texture mapping coordinates, normal vectors, and displacement mapping.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Polygon meshes may be represented in a variety of ways, using different methods to store the vertex, edge and face data.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Each representation has advantages and disadvantages, discussed in Smith (2006).
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of vertices connected to other vertices.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] This is the simplest representation, but not widely used since the face and edge information is implicit.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Thus, it is necessary to traverse the data in order to generate a list of faces for rendering.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] In addition, operations on edges and faces are not easily accomplished.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] However, VV meshes benefit from small storage space and efficient morphing of shape.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows a four-sided box as represented by a VV mesh.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Each vertex indexes its neighboring vertices.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The last two vertices, 8 and 9 at the top and bottom center of the "box-cylinder", have four connected vertices rather than five.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] A general system must be able to handle an arbitrary number of vertices connected to any given vertex.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] For a complete description of VV meshes see Smith (2006).
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of faces and a set of vertices.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] This is the most widely used mesh representation, being the input typically accepted by modern graphics hardware.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes improve on VV mesh for modelling in that they allow explicit lookup of the vertices of a face, and the faces surrounding a vertex.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" example as an FV mesh.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Vertex v5 is highlighted to show the faces that surround it.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Notice that, in this example, every face is required to have exactly 3 vertices.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] However, this does not mean every vertex has the same number of surrounding faces.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] For rendering, the face list is usually transmitted to the GPU as a set of indices to vertices, and the vertices are sent as position/color/normal structures (in the figure, only position is given).
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] This has the benefit that changes in shape, but not geometry, can be dynamically updated by simply resending the vertex data without updating the face connectivity.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Modelling requires easy traversal of all structures.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] With face-vertex meshes it is easy to find the vertices of a face.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Also, the vertex list contains a list of faces connected to each vertex.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Unlike VV meshes, both faces and vertices are explicit, so locating neighboring faces and vertices is constant time.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] However, the edges are implicit, so a search is still needed to find all the faces surrounding a given face.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Other dynamic operations, such as splitting or merging a face, are also difficult with face-vertex meshes.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Introduced by Baumgart in 1975, winged-edge meshes explicitly represent the vertices, faces, and edges of a mesh.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] This representation is widely used in modelling programs to provide the greatest flexibility in dynamically changing the mesh geometry, because split and merge operations can be done quickly.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Their primary drawback is large storage requirements and increased complexity due to maintaining many indices.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] A good discussion of implementation issues of Winged-edge meshes may be found in the book *Graphics Gems II*.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes address the issue of traversing from edge to edge, and providing an ordered set of faces around an edge.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] For any given edge, the number of outgoing edges may be arbitrary.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] To simplify this, winged-edge meshes provide only four, the nearest clockwise and counter-clockwise edges at each end.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The other edges may be traversed incrementally.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The information for each edge therefore resembles a butterfly, hence "winged-edge" meshes.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" as a winged-edge mesh.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The total data for an edge consists of 2 vertices (endpoints), 2 faces (on each side), and 4 edges (winged-edge).
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Rendering of winged-edge meshes for graphics hardware requires generating a face index list, which is usually done only when the geometry changes.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are ideally suited for dynamic geometry, such as subdivision surfaces and interactive modelling, since changes to the mesh can occur locally.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Traversal across the mesh, as might be needed for collision detection, can be accomplished efficiently.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are not the only representation which allows for dynamic changes to geometry.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] A representation which combines winged-edge meshes and face-vertex meshes is the render dynamic mesh (RDM), which explicitly stores both, the vertices of a face and faces of a vertex (like FV meshes), and the faces and vertices of an edge (like winged-edge).
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] RDM's require less storage space than standard winged-edge meshes, and can be directly rendered by graphics hardware since the face list contains an index of vertices.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] In addition, traversal from vertex to face is explicit (constant time), as is from face to vertex.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] RDM's do not require the four outgoing edges since these can be found by traversing from edge to face, then face to neighboring edge.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] RDM's benefit from the features of winged-edge meshes by allowing for geometry to be dynamically updated.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] See Tobler & Maierhofer (WSCG 2006) for more details.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The notation *avg(V,V)* means the average number of vertices connected to a given vertex; *avg(E,V)* means the average number of edges connected to a given vertex, and *avg(F,V)* is the average number of faces connected to a given vertex.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The notation "V → f1, f2, f3, ... → v1, v2, v3, ..." describes that a traversal across multiple elements is required to perform the operation.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] For example, to get "all vertices around a given vertex V" using the face-vertex mesh, it is necessary to first find the faces around the given vertex V using the vertex list.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Then, from those faces, use the face list to find the vertices around them.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes explicitly store nearly all information, and other operations always traverse to the edge first to get additional info.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are the only representation that explicitly stores the neighboring vertices of a given vertex.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] As the mesh representations become more complex (from left to right in the summary), the amount of information explicitly stored increases.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] This gives more direct, constant time, access to traversal and topology of various elements but at the cost of increased overhead and space in maintaining indices properly.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] As a general rule, face-vertex meshes are used whenever an object must be rendered on graphics hardware that does not change geometry (connectivity), but may deform or morph shape (vertex positions) such as real-time rendering of static or morphing objects.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge or render dynamic meshes are used when the geometry changes, such as in interactive modeling packages or for computing subdivision surfaces.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are ideal for efficient, complex changes in geometry or topology so long as hardware rendering is not of concern.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes store faces in an ordered, yet independent, way so that the mesh can be transmitted in pieces.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] The order of faces may be spatial, spectral, or based on other properties of the mesh.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes allow a very large mesh to be rendered even while it is still being loaded.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Progressive meshes transmit the vertex and face data with increasing levels of detail.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Unlike *streaming meshes*, progressive meshes give the overall shape of the entire object, but at a low level of detail.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Additional data, new edges and faces, progressively increase the detail of the mesh.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes transmit progressive changes to a mesh as a set of normal displacements from a base mesh.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] With this technique, a series of textures represent the desired incremental modifications.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes are compact, since only a single scalar value is needed to express displacement.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] However, the technique requires a complex series of transformations to create the displacement textures.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] There exist many different file formats for storing polygon mesh data.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Each format is most effective when used for the purpose intended by its creator.
[src:obj-3d-format/polygon-mesh] Popular formats include .fbx, .dae, .obj, and .stl.
